text: If you do any searching,  and you always do, regexes are indispensable. Every decent editor supports regex search. It would be criminal to waste your time and not use them wherever you could. One thing I miss though is not all languages support matching regexes for example if you have function in any language which has same scope delimiter as inner scopes, say {}, there aren't many languages that support regexes to match them and find start and end of function.  You can use forward looking regex but it is neither efficient nor simple.

author: @shivanshsahu4908
text: Regular Expression Notes  . or period is used to match any character  \d matches any digits from 0-9 \D matches anything except a digit(0-9)  \w matches word characters (A-Z, a-z, 0-9 and _) \W matches anything except word characters (!, @, #, $, %, ^, &, *, (, ), -, +, =, ~, `, ?, /, ., >, , <, ", ", ', ', ;, :, {, }, [, ], /, |)  \s matches whitespace \S matches anything except whitespace  \b matches word boundary (\ba will select only the second a from 'bab a' because it is not connecting with any word in the beginning) \B matches anything without word boundary (\Ba will select only the first a from 'bab a' because it is not seperated by whitespace from any other character)  ^ or caret matches anything at the start of a line(^S in 'Shivansh         Shivansh' will select the S of the 1st Shivansh bcoz it is starting the particular line)  $ matches anything at the end of a line($h in 'Shivansh         Shivansh' will select the h of the 2nd Shivansh bcoz it is ending the line)  *CHARACTER SETS* [] or character set can be used to match one of the multiple options specified in it ([-.] in 'Shivansh-' 'Shivansh.' matches both - and . in both the strings respectively)  	- inside a character set [] can be used to specify a range of values ([A-Z], [a-f], [0-5], etc.) 	^ inside a character set [] matches anything that is not the specified value ([^a] will not match any lowercase a in the document)  | can be used to specify many scenarios and only one of them will be selected (  M(r | s | rs) this selects all Mr Ms and Mrs without any errors) () can be used to group stuff up and apply a single property to them (  (A-Z)? in this property, it is not necessary that the text needs to be form A-Z because it is added with the ? property that is described later)  Quantifiers  * - 0 or more + - 1 or more ? - 0 or one {4} -  exact number (3,10) - range of numbers (min , max)  To replace selected stuff to any text and change it to any particular group of the regular expression Text: $1(for atom) or \1 (for most of the other editors) can be written, this will replace everything the regular expression is capturing and change it to whatever the first group is in the regular expression  Hope these notes helped you!

author: @klauswerner
text: The most I us regular expressions, is to manipulate words that came in the index of the search engine in my shop, or to manipulate the search strings the user puts in. That helps us so much to make the search engine better. Different writings in the search string, wrong writing, shortcuts in product-textes, an so on... A german example: \b([0-9])[ ]?reihig[e]?[mnrs]?\b -> $1reihig \b([0-9]+[,]?[0-9]*)( )?( kg|kilo)\b -> $1kg So even what the the User puts in, the search engine gets a standardised Input for the search engine.

author: @peterlewerin4213
text: This is a good introduction, but it distresses me that so many seem to draw the conclusion that regexps are simple to work with. I have been programming for ~40 years and used many regexp-based tools like awk, grep, parser generators, etc, and I consider regexps to be very insidious. Quite manageable, of course, but they *will* bite you if you aren't careful. Viewers who are RE beginners should keep in mind that these are simple, clear examples to show the basics of regexps. These examples are riding a bike with training wheels on an empty street. A lot more effort is required for anything beyond trivial matching (such as finding text in an editor). For reliable data capture, even the more complex email-matching regexp introduced at 28:57, for instance, is inadequate.

author: @vjlenin
text: There is one observation if someone wants to look at it. Imagine a list of names like: Mr. Jack Mrs. Jones Then the regex M(r|rs|s)\.* ....  tries to match the "Mr" first in both names. So right after matching Mr, it is looking for zero or more dots and then proceeds further. It has never matched "Mrs" in full. This is the issue I have in Notepad++. I don't know if anyone saw this. But when I change the order of the regex as M(rs|r|s), it tries to match "Mrs" first, and if not found, matches "Mr". This way, it works correctly.
